SIMPLE: repel
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Repel
<hw>Re**pel"</hw> <pr>(r?-p?l")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Repelled</conjf>
<pr>(-p?ld")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Repelling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>repellere</ets>,
<ets>repulsum</ets>; pref. <ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>pellere</ets> to
drive. See <er>Pulse</er> a beating, and cf. <er>Repulse</er>,
<er>Repeal</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To drive back; to force to
return; to check the advance of; to repulse as, to <xex>repel</xex> an
enemy or an assailant.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hippomedon <qex>repelled</qex> the hostile tide.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>repelled</qex> each other strongly, and yet attracted
each other strongly.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To resist or oppose effectually; <as>as, to
<ex>repel</ex> an assault, an encroachment, or an
argument</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[He] gently <qex>repelled</qex> their entreaties.</q>
<rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Tu repulse; resist; oppose; reject;
refuse.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Repel</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Repel
<hw>Re*pel"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To act with force in opposition
to force impressed; to exercise repulsion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Repellency</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Repellence</ent>⟦br⟧
